text: Ok, but honestly, how many movies have bashed us over the head with this message WITHOUT making the main character(s)' goal being pretty and perfect? This movie is saying from the start that being "ugly" doesn't mean you're not beautiful. This is good. Kids need this kind of message, and they need it stated in this blatant and obvious way. This could help cement the idea that looks don't matter. This could be so inspirational to victims of racial abuse, accidents that left disfigurations or scarring, and people with body-image issues. Don't hate just because it isn't original. Originality doesn't sell. People buy what they like, and they like what's familiar. Movies need to sell or the companies will go out of business. It's marketing, not plot construction.

text: So, I'm not sure if I like the whole musical take on this movie but I won't allow that to stop me from looking down at it so quickly. Obviously you have the main antagonist who is pretty much a physical representation of modern day society, looking down at different people or people who have such different outlooks on life. The whole positive vibe that this trailer advertises definetely makes me want to watch this movie. I will watch the movie but I can't say if I will enjoy all the singing in such an important topic in today's hateful society.
